================= FACTORY vs STRATEGY (SHORT & CLEAR) =================

1. PURPOSE
--------------------------------------------------
Factory Pattern  : Creates objects
Strategy Pattern : Changes behavior (logic/algorithm)

--------------------------------------------------

2. WHO DECIDES IMPLEMENTATION?
--------------------------------------------------
Factory Pattern  : Factory class decides
Strategy Pattern : Client decides

--------------------------------------------------

3. HOW IT WORKS
--------------------------------------------------
Factory Pattern:
    Payment p = PaymentFactory.getPayment("credit");
    // You pass a TYPE → Factory returns object

Strategy Pattern:
    PaymentStrategy s = new CreditCardPayment();
    PaymentGateway g = new PaymentGateway(s);
    // You pass the IMPLEMENTATION itself

--------------------------------------------------

4. INPUT TYPE
--------------------------------------------------
Factory Pattern  : String / enum / identifier
Strategy Pattern : Object (actual class instance)

--------------------------------------------------

5. FOCUS
--------------------------------------------------
Factory Pattern  : Object Creation
Strategy Pattern : Runtime Behavior Switching

--------------------------------------------------

6. DEPENDENCY
--------------------------------------------------
Factory Pattern:
    Client depends on Factory

Strategy Pattern:
    Context depends on Strategy interface
    Client injects implementation

--------------------------------------------------

7. REAL MEANING (1 LINE)
--------------------------------------------------
Factory  = "Give me an object based on type"
Strategy = "Use this behavior to perform task"

=======================================================================